<h3>Writing fractions</h3>
<p>Every fraction has two parts: a top number and a bottom number. In math =
terms, these are called the <strong>numerator</strong> and the <strong>deno=
minator</strong>. Don't worry too much about remembering those names. As lo=
ng as you remember what each number means, you can understand any fraction.=
</p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 673; margin-top: 0;"><img loadin=
g=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearnfree.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1=
_2_numdenom.png" alt=3D"Numerator =3D Top Number ; Denominator =3D Bottom N=
umber" width=3D"673" height=3D"300"></div>
<p>As you saw in the slideshow, the <strong>bottom number</strong>, or deno=
minator, is the<strong> number of parts</strong> a whole is divided into. I=
n our pizza example, we said each slice was <strong>1/8</strong> of the piz=
za. The <span class=3D"glossaryterm">denominator</span> was<span class=3D"e=
quation"> <strong>8</strong></span>, since the pizza was divided into<span =
class=3D"equation"><strong> 8</strong> </span>slices.</p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 481; margin-top: 0;" rel=3D"widt=
h: 481; margin-top: 0;"><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearn=
free.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1_1_pizza8.png" alt=3D"1/8: 8 is the deno=
minator" width=3D"481" height=3D"300"></div>
<p>The top number, or numerator, refers to a certain number of those parts.=
 It lets us know how much we're talking about. Since we're talking about <s=
trong>one</strong> slice of pizza, our <span class=3D"glossaryterm">numerat=
or</span> is <strong>1.</strong></p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 481; margin-top: 0;"><img loadin=
g=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearnfree.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1=
_1_pizza1.png" alt=3D"1/8: 1 is the numerator" width=3D"481" height=3D"300"=
></div>
<p>Let's look at another example. What if we divided the same pizza into <s=
pan class=3D"equation"><strong>12</strong> </span>slices instead of <strong=
>8</strong>? If we took one slice, that would be <span class=3D"equation">1=
/12</span> of the pizza=E2=80=94<strong>1</strong> slice out of the <strong=
>12</strong> total slices. No matter what fraction you're trying to write, =
you always write it the same way=E2=80=94with the number of parts on the bo=
ttom, and the parts you're referring to on top.</p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 481; margin-top: 0;" rel=3D"widt=
h: 481; margin-top: 0;"><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearn=
free.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1_1_pizza12.png" width=3D"481" height=3D"=
300"></div>
