<h4>Mixed numbers</h4>
<p>Sometimes you might see a fraction next to a whole number. We call this =
a <strong>mixed number</strong>. We'll talk more about mixed numbers in the=
 <a href=3D"http://www.gcflearnfree.org/fractions/comparing-and-reducing-fr=
actions/1/">next lesson</a>. For now, we'll concentrate on learning how to =
read them. Let's take a look at this example:</p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 664; margin-top: 0;"><img loadin=
g=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearnfree.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1=
_2_twoandahalf.png" alt=3D"2 1/2" width=3D"664" height=3D"320"></div>
<p><strong><span class=3D"equation">2 1/2</span> </strong>is a mixed number=
. If we say we have <span class=3D"equation">2 1/2</span> pizzas, it means =
we have <span class=3D"equation"><strong>2</strong></span> whole pizzas and=
 <span class=3D"equation">1/2</span> of another pizza. You can read<span cl=
ass=3D"equation"> 2 1/2</span> like this: <strong>two-and-a-half</strong>.<=
/p>
<p>Let's try another example. What if you pour <span class=3D"equation">1</=
span> whole cup of tea, then fill only <span class=3D"equation">2/3</span> =
of another cup? You could write that situation like this:</p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 548; margin-top: 0;"><img loadin=
g=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearnfree.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1=
_2_oneandtwothirds.png" alt=3D"1 2/3" width=3D"548" height=3D"291"></div>
<p>You'd read <span class=3D"equation">1 2/3</span> like this: <strong>one =
and two-thirds. </strong>Remember, the whole number is always <strong>first=
</strong>.</p>
