<h3>Whole fractions</h3>
<p>So far, you've learned that a fraction is a <strong>part</strong> of a w=
hole. For example, <span class=3D"equation">3/4</span> means you have <stro=
ng>three</strong> <strong>parts</strong> out of <strong>four</strong> <stro=
ng>parts total</strong>. But what if you had a fraction like this?</p>
<p class=3D"probCentered">8/8</p>
<p>In this example, we have <strong>eight parts</strong> out of <strong>eig=
ht parts</strong> <strong>total</strong>. If the top number and the bottom =
number of a fraction are the same, then the fraction is equal to <span clas=
s=3D"equation">1</span>. That's because you have <strong>every part</strong=
> of the fraction, or <strong>one whole thing</strong>. This is sometimes k=
nown as a <strong>whole</strong> <strong>fraction</strong>.</p>
<p>So if you had <strong>eight</strong> slices of pizza out of <strong>eigh=
t</strong> <strong>total</strong>, you'd have <strong>one</strong> whole pi=
zza.</p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 550; margin-top: 0;"><img loadin=
g=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearnfree.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1=
_3_parts_wholeB.png"></div>
<p>Let's look at another example: <span class=3D"equation">8/8 </span>and<s=
pan class=3D"equation"> 2/2</span>. While these fractions may look differen=
t, they're actually just two ways of saying the same thing. Because these a=
re whole fractions, <span class=3D"equation">8/8</span> and <span class=3D"=
equation">2/2</span> are both equal to <span class=3D"equation">1</span>. A=
nd because they're both equal to <span class=3D"equation">1</span>, they're=
 also equal to each other.</p>
<div class=3D"centerImage" style=3D"width: 550; margin-top: 0;" rel=3D"widt=
h: 550; margin-top: 0;"><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://media.gcflearn=
free.org/ctassets/topics/231/Frac_1_3_equivalentB.png"></div>
